<!-- ============ HERO ============ -->
<header class="hero">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="eyebrow">The LIHTC Expiration Crisis</div>
    <h1>We are losing affordable housing <span>faster than we build it</span>.</h1>
    <p class="deck">
      Not by accident. Public money pays to create affordable homes — and then, thirty years later,
      the affordability simply expires and the market takes them back.
      It is happening now, it is accelerating, and almost nobody knows.
    </p>
    <div class="cta-row">
      <a href="/find-your-building/" class="btn btn-gold">Find your building</a>
      <a href="#how" class="btn btn-outline">How is this legal?</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</header>

<!-- ============ HOW IT WORKS — the missing piece ============ -->
<section class="section" id="how">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="eyebrow dark">How it works</div>
    <h2 style="margin-top:14px;max-width:22ch">"You've lived there thirty years. How can anyone make you leave?"</h2>
    <p class="lead" style="max-width:62ch">
      This is the question everyone asks, and the answer is the reason this website exists.
      Most people assume affordable housing is <em>permanently</em> affordable. It isn't.
      It is a contract, and the contract has an end date.
    </p>

    <div class="how">
      <div>
        <div class="n">1</div>
        <h3>The public pays to build it.</h3>
        <p>A developer gets federal tax credits — public money — to build or convert a building into affordable housing. Investors buy the credits. That's what pays for the building.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="n">2</div>
        <h3>In exchange, rents stay low — for thirty years.</h3>
        <p>Low-income tenants move in at restricted rents. They stay. They raise children, bury parents, get old. The neighbourhood changes around them. For thirty years, the system works exactly as designed.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="n">3</div>
        <h3>Then the thirty years end.</h3>
        <p>And that's it. The rent restrictions lift. The owner can charge whatever the market will bear. There is no notice requirement, no agency with a duty to act, and <strong>no remedy written into the law</strong> for the people still living there.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pull red" style="margin-top:36px">
      Nobody is breaking the law. That is the entire problem.
      <span style="display:block;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;margin-top:12px;opacity:.92">
        The expiration is not a loophole, an oversight, or a bad landlord.
        It is what the statute says. It was designed this way, and nobody wrote down what happens next.
      </span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

