<!-- ============ IT WAS AVOIDABLE ============ -->
<section class="failure">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <span class="lab">System failure</span>
    <h2>Public dollars are used to create housing that expires after thirty years.</h2>
    <p class="sub">
      Every clock in this programme is the investor's clock. Ten years of tax credits. Fifteen years
      of enforceable compliance. Thirty years, and the financing has finished doing what financing does.
    </p>
    <p class="sub">
      Not one of those numbers is about a person. Nobody asked how long a tenant lives somewhere.
      Nobody asked what happens to the 62-year-old on the last day of year thirty.
    </p>

    <div class="verdict">
      We are not losing affordable housing by accident.<br>Current policy ensures it.
    </div>

    <h2 style="margin-top:56px;font-size:clamp(26px,3.2vw,34px)">And every part of this was foreseeable.</h2>
    <p class="sub">
      You did not need a crystal ball. The term was written as thirty years. The people moving in
      were in their thirties, forties and fifties. It required no special insight to work out that
      most of them would still be alive, still need somewhere to live, and be older and poorer when
      the clock ran out.
    </p>
    <p class="sub">
      <strong style="color:#fff">We also knew how to do it properly, and other states did.</strong>
      Vermont has required affordability <em>in perpetuity</em> since the early 2000s — and gets two
      to three times more developer demand than it has credits to award. Oregon requires sixty years.
      California fifty-five. The average state term is about forty-two.
    </p>
    <div class="verdict" style="border-left-color:var(--red)">
      New York requires the federal minimum — thirty years.<br>
      <span style="font-size:17px;font-weight:400;display:block;margin-top:10px;color:#a9bad3">
        Below the national average, in the most expensive housing market in the country.
        Nobody in Washington made us do that.
      </span>
    </div>
    <p class="sub" style="margin-top:26px">
      This was not a failure of knowledge. It was a failure of will — and it can be reversed by the
      same people who chose it.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ============ THE CASE STUDY ============ -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <div class="eyebrow dark">One example, of thousands</div>
    <h2 style="margin-top:14px">What it looks like when the clock runs out</h2>
    <p class="lead">
      This site is run by a tenant of an expiring building. Not because it's special —
      because it's <em>ordinary</em>. This is what the policy does when it arrives at a front door.
    </p>

    <div class="case">
      <div class="lab">The story of 63 Tiffany Place</div>
      <h3>In 1994, nobody wanted to live here.</h3>
      <p>
        The building was a failed luxury condo conversion that went to foreclosure. It only became
        affordable housing because there was no other way to make the numbers work. Seventy families
        moved in. <strong>The New York Times wrote about it as a model of how well these tax credit
        programmes worked.</strong>
      </p>
      <p>
        For thirty years, it did work. Tenants raised children, buried parents, and turned a
        neighbourhood people avoided into one of the most desirable in Brooklyn. Rents rose gently —
        <em>below inflation</em> — exactly as designed.
      </p>

      <div class="rentline">
        <div><div class="v">$604</div><div class="k">rent in 1994</div></div>
        <div><div class="v">$1,200</div><div class="k">rent thirty years later</div></div>
        <div><div class="v red">$3,214–$6,300</div><div class="k">market rate on that block today</div></div>
      </div>

      <p style="margin-top:24px">
        Then the thirty years ran out — and the same programme that housed those families became the
        reason they could lose their homes. <strong>Nobody did anything wrong. The rent was paid, on
        time, for three decades, through the pandemic.</strong> There was simply a date, and after
        it, the market.
      </p>
      <p>
        Residents who moved in in their forties, fifties and sixties are now in their seventies,
        eighties and nineties. One of the founders of the tenants association travelled to Albany to
        lobby, and died before finding out how it ends.
      </p>
      <p style="margin-top:20px;font-size:15px;color:var(--slate)">
        <a href="https://save63tiffany.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener" style="color:var(--navy);font-weight:700">The full story of that building →</a>
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="pull" style="margin-top:34px">
      That building is not the story. It is one example of the story —
      and there are hundreds more in this state where the same clock is running,
      and almost none of them know about each other.
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ============ WHAT MUST CHANGE ============ -->
<section class="section band">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="eyebrow dark">What must change</div>
    <h2 style="margin-top:14px">Four demands.</h2>

    <div class="cards">
      <div class="card">
        <div class="meta">Demand 01</div>
        <h3>Extend affordability beyond thirty years — or make it permanent</h3>
        <p><strong>Vermont requires affordability in perpetuity</strong> and still gets two to three times more developer demand than it has credits to award. Oregon requires 60 years. California 55. The state average is 42. <strong>New York requires the federal minimum of 30.</strong></p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="meta">Demand 02</div>
        <h3>Give tenants and nonprofits the first chance to buy</h3>
        <p>Pass <strong>TOPA</strong> at the state level and <strong>COPA</strong> in the city. And fund them — a right to buy is worthless without the money to buy. The city's acquisition fund is capitalised at $13 million.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="meta">Demand 03</div>
        <h3>Treat expiring LIHTC as a housing emergency</h3>
        <p>Not a future risk. It is happening on a published schedule, right now, and every year of delay is thousands of homes we don't get back.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="cards" style="grid-template-columns:1fr;margin-top:22px">
      <div class="card">
        <div class="meta">Demand 04</div>
        <h3>A right to know your expiration date</h3>
        <p>Tenants are never told. Landlords sometimes don't know. In my building, the attorneys on both sides disagreed on the date and it was settled by <em>negotiation</em>. New York is about to give 421-a tenants this right in writing — and leave LIHTC tenants out of it. <a href="/articles/2026-07-13-nobody-knew-the-date/" style="color:var(--navy);font-weight:700">Read what happened →</a></p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pull red" style="margin-top:36px">
      New York's thirty-year term is not federal law. It is written into the state's own rulebook —
      the Qualified Allocation Plan — by a state agency.
      <span style="display:block;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;margin-top:12px;opacity:.92">
        Changing it does not need Congress. It does not need a bill.
        It needs New York to write a different number in a document it already controls.
      </span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ============ URGENCY ============ -->
<section class="section" style="background:#fff;border-top:1px solid var(--line)">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <div class="eyebrow dark" style="color:var(--red)">Why now</div>
    <h2 style="margin-top:14px">Every year we wait, the homes are gone for good.</h2>
    <p class="lead">
      This is not a crisis that waits politely for the movement to be ready. The expirations are on a
      schedule that was set thirty years ago, and they arrive whether or not anyone has the votes yet.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      And once a building goes, <strong>it does not come back.</strong> There is no mechanism to
      reclaim it. You would have to buy it at market price, from an owner who now has every reason not
      to sell — in a market the tenants themselves made expensive by staying.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      The people in these buildings are the least able to absorb the loss: <strong>over half of LIHTC
      tenants earn below 30% of area median income.</strong> Many are old. Many are disabled. Many
      have nowhere in this city to go, and no city to go to.
    </p>

    <div class="pull red">
      This was avoidable. It is still fixable.
      <span style="display:block;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;margin-top:12px;opacity:.92">
        But not for much longer, and not for the buildings whose clock ran out while we were
        deciding whether it mattered.
      </span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

